  "chunk_index": 28,
  "summary": "On a path leading toward a house, Mickey and Tina engage in a tense confrontation. Mickey questions Tina regarding how she knows he was present on the night of her mother's murder. Tina avoids a direct answer, instead expressing concern for Hester Hurst and Don Craig. She notes that while it was previously believed that Jacqueline killed the mother, it is now clear that Jacqueline did not.\n\nBelow a lookout on a riverbank, Don Craig attempts to discuss the morning's police questioning with Hester Hurst. Hester expresses a desire to forget the incident, but Don insists she face reality. He asks Hester who last saw her mother alive, and she replies it was herself around seven o'clock, just before she went to the theater. When Don asks if she had a reason to kill her mother, Hester matter-of-factly admits she often had violent dreams about killing her. Don, acting with the intensity of a doctor interested in the case, pleads with Hester to tell him the truth, promising to protect and help her if she is responsible. Hester mocks his persistence and flees up the path, leaving Don frustrated.\n\nElsewhere, Philip Darland and Mary argue about whether to stay at the scene of the murder. Mary finds the location gloomy and oppressive, wanting to return home to her household duties. Philip expresses a petulant desire to stay because he finds the situation interesting. He later apologizes to Mary, lamenting how his life and his ability to be his former self have changed.",
